this surname are formally difficult to distinguish from those in 1 above.","English: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Pernel</i>, see   Parnell  ."]},{"name":"Pernell","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Warwickshire): variant of   Parnell  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Purnell","meanings":["English: variant of   Parnell  ."]},{"name":"Pennell","meanings":["English (especially southeastern):","metronym from the Middle English female personal name <i>Pennel</i> (an assimilated form of   Parnell  ).","habitational name from Penn Hall in Pensax (Worcestershire), or from either of two places called Penhill in Devon and Yorkshire, or possibly from Pendle in Lancashire. All of the placenames probably derive from British <i>penn</i> ‘head’ + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Petronilla","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old female name; an Italian diminutive formed from Pietro, i.e. Peter."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":4,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":29,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":42,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":51,"year":"1337","toYear":"1